    <h2>Edithvale — Wetlands Backdrop, Bay Corridor Suburb, Postwar Stock, Cold and Damp Winter Pattern</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Edithvale is a bayside suburb on Melbourne's south-eastern bay corridor, notable for the Edithvale-Seaford Wetlands that border the suburb to the east — a large wetland reserve that creates a distinctive cold and damp microclimate for the residential streets between the wetlands and the bay foreshore. The housing stock is predominantly postwar brick homes from the 1950s through the 1970s, with some later development on former market garden land as the suburb filled out. A proportion of Edithvale homes include original open fireplaces or have slow combustion heaters installed, and the suburb's position between the bay and the wetlands means winter cold is amplified by both bay southerlies and the damp cold air that settles off the wetland reserve on still nights. The combination of bay humidity and wetland damp creates an environment where chimney components deteriorate more quickly than in drier inland suburbs — annual inspection is the correct standard for Edithvale properties. We service Edithvale and the surrounding bay corridor suburbs regularly.</p></div>
  </section>

